Split loop refactoring is a technique for improving the structure of existing code by splitting a loop into two or more separate loops, in order to improve the readability and maintainability of the code. This can make the code easier to understand and extend, as well as reduce duplication and improve the encapsulation of the code.

Here is an example of split loop refactoring in Java:

Suppose we have the following code that calculates the sum of the squares of the even numbers in a given list:
```
public class SumSquares {
  public static int calculate(List<Integer> numbers) {
    int sum = 0;
    for (int i = 0; i < numbers.size(); i++) {
      int number = numbers.get(i);
      if (number % 2 == 0) {
        sum += number * number;
      }
    }
    return sum;
  }
}
```
We can improve the structure of this code by splitting the loop into two separate loops: one loop for filtering out the even numbers and another loop for calculating the sum of the squares:
```
public class SumSquares {
  public static int calculate(List<Integer> numbers) {
    List<Integer> evenNumbers = new ArrayList<>();
    for (int i = 0; i < numbers.size(); i++) {
      int number = numbers.get(i);
      if (number % 2 == 0) {
        evenNumbers.add(number);
      }
    }

    int sum = 0;
    for (int i = 0; i < evenNumbers.size(); i++) {
      sum += evenNumbers.get(i) * evenNumbers.get(i);
    }
    return sum;
  }
}
```
In this refactored version of the code, the loop has been split into two separate loops: the first loop filters out the even numbers and stores them in a separate list, and the second loop calculates the sum of the squares of the even numbers. This makes the code easier to understand and maintain, as the logic for filtering out the even numbers and calculating the sum of the squares is now separated into two distinct loops. It also reduces duplication, as the logic for filtering out the even numbers can now be reused in other parts of the code without having to copy and paste the same logic. Finally, it improves the encapsulation of the code, as the logic for filtering out the even numbers is now self-contained within the first loop and does not depend on any external state.

