Here is a possible optimization of the function:
```
const groupLogsByType = (rawLogs: T.BuildLog[], filterType: FilterState): FilteredLog[] => {
  // Return early if filterType is 'all' or if rawLogs is empty
  if (filterType === 'all' || rawLogs.length === 0) {
    return [{ hidden: false, logs: rawLogs }];
  }

  const groups: FilteredLog[] = [];

  // Use a single loop to iterate through the rawLogs and create groups
  let currentGroupType: FilterState = 'all';
  let currentGroup: BuildLogWithIndex[] = [];
  for (let i = 0; i < rawLogs.length; i++) {
    const log = { ...rawLogs[i], index: i };
    let logType: FilterState = 'all';
    if (log.error) {
      logType = 'errors';
    } else if (log.warning) {
      logType = 'warnings';
    }

    if (logType !== currentGroupType) {
      groups.push({
        hidden: currentGroupType !== filterType,
        logs: currentGroup,
      });
      currentGroup = [log];
      currentGroupType = logType;
    } else {
      currentGroup.push(log);
    }
  }

  // Push the last group after the loop
  groups.push({
    hidden: currentGroupType !== filterType,
    logs: currentGroup,
  });

  // Group together neighboring groups that are either both hidden or visible.
  const compactedGroups = groups.reduce<FilteredLog[]>((prev, cur) => {
    const isCurrentGroupHidden = cur.hidden;
    const previousGroup = prev.at(-1);
    const isPreviousGroupHidden =
      previousGroup === undefined ? isCurrentGroupHidden : previousGroup.hidden;

    if (isCurrentGroupHidden === isPreviousGroupHidden) {
      const newGroups = prev;
      if (newGroups.length === 0) {
        return [cur];
      }
      newGroups.at(-1)?.logs.push(...cur.logs);
      return newGroups;
    }
    return prev.concat(cur);
  }, []);

  return compactedGroups;
};
```
The main changes are:

1. Return early if filterType is 'all' or if rawLogs is empty, as this condition is checked at the start of the function.
2. Use a single loop to iterate through the rawLogs and create groups, which eliminates the need to map each log to an object with an index and check the length of the logs.
3. Push the last group after the loop, instead of checking for it in the loop.

Moving a class to a header file is a common practice in C++ programming. It helps to organize the code and makes it easier to reuse the class in other parts of the program. Here are the steps to move a class to a header file:

1. Create a new header file with a ".h" or ".hpp" extension. For example, if your class is called "MyClass", you could create a file named "MyClass.h".
2. In the header file, start by including any necessary header files that are needed for your class. For example, if your class uses the "iostream" library, you would include the following line at the top of your header file:
```c++
#include <iostream>
```
3. Next, copy the entire class declaration from your source file (".cpp" file) into the header file. The class declaration should include the class name, any member variables, and any member functions. For example:
```c++
class MyClass {
  public:
    MyClass();
    void myFunction();
  private:
    int myVariable;
};
```
4. Remove the class declaration from your source file.
5. In your source file, include the header file at the top of the file using the "#include" directive. For example:
```c++
#include "MyClass.h"
```
6. Recompile your program to make sure there are no syntax errors.
7. You should now be able to use your class in your source code by creating an instance of the class and calling its member functions. For example:
```c++
MyClass myObject;
myObject.myFunction();
```
That's it! By moving your class to a header file, you have made it easier to reuse and maintain your code.

