Here's an example of the `VideoCache` component:
```
import { useEffect } from 'react';

const VideoCache = () => {
  useEffect(() => {
    const videoUrl = 'https://example.com/video.mp4';

    // Fetch the video from the specified URL
    fetch(videoUrl)
      .then(response => {
        if (!response.ok) {
          throw new Error('Failed to fetch video');
        }

        // Create a new ReadableStream of the video
        const videoStream = response.body;

        // Extract the first few seconds of the video
        const videoSlice = videoStream.slice(0, 3);

        // Create a new cache object and store the extracted video slice in it
        caches.open('video-cache')
          .then(cache => cache.put(videoUrl, new Response(videoSlice)));
      })
      .catch(error => {
        console.error(error);
      });
  }, []);

  return null;
};

export default VideoCache;
```
Note that this example is using the `caches` API, which is an experimental feature and may not be supported in all browsers.

You should also make sure that the URL you use is same origin or you have CORS enabled on the server.

